\layout Title

Notes Relating to Newton Series for the Riemann Zeta Function
\layout Author

Linas Vepstas
\layout Date

August 6, 2006
\layout Abstract

This paper consists of the extended working notes and observations made
 during the development of a joint paper with Philippe Flajolet on the Riemann
 zeta function.
 Much of the core of that paper is reproduced here, along with the explorations
 of tangents shooting off in various directions.
 
\layout Abstract

The finite differences or Newton series of certain expressions involving
 the Riemann zeta function are explored.
 These series may be given an asymptotic expansion by converting them to
 Norlund-Rice integrals and applying saddle-point integration techniques.
 Numerical evaluation is used to confirm the appropriateness of the asymptotic
 expansion.
 The results extend on previous results for such series, and a general form
 for Dirichlet L-functins is given.
 Curiously, because successive terms in the asymptotic expansion are exponential
ly small, these series lead to simple near-identities.
 A resemblance to similar near-identities arising in complex multiplication
 is noted.
 
\layout Section

Introduction
\layout Standard

The binomial coefficient is implicated in various fractal phenomena, and
 the Berry conjecture [ref] suggests that the zeros of the Riemann zeta
 function correspond to the chaotic spectrum of an unknown quantization
 of some simple chaotic mechanical system.
 Thus, on vague and general principles, one might be lead to explore Newton
 series involving the Riemann zeta function.
 Of some curiosity is the series
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta(s)=\frac{1}{s-1}+\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}(-1)^{n}\,\frac{b_{n}}{n!}\,(s)_{n}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $(s)_{n}=s(s-1)\cdots(s-n+1)$
\end_inset 

 is the falling Pochhammer symbol.
 Note the general resemblance to a Taylor's series, with the Pochhammer
 symbol taking the place of the monomial.
 Such general types of resemblances are the key idea underlying the so-called
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

umbral calculus
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

Here, the constants 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset 

 play a role analogous to the Stieltjes constants of the Taylor expansion.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset 

 have several remarkable properties.
 Unlike the Stieltjes constants, they may be written as a finite sum over
 well-known constants:
\begin_inset Formula \[
b_{n}=n(1-\gamma-H_{n-1})-\frac{1}{2}+\sum_{k=2}^{n}(-)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\zeta(k)\]

\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n>0$
\end_inset 

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H_{n}=\sum_{m=1}^{n}\frac{1}{m}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 are the harmonic numbers.
 The first few values are 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
b_{0} & = & \frac{1}{2}\label{eq:}\\
b_{1} & = & -\gamma+\frac{1}{2}\\
b_{2} & = & -2\gamma-\frac{1}{2}+\zeta(2)\\
b_{3} & = & -3\gamma-2-\zeta(3)+3\zeta(2)\\
b_{4} & = & -4\gamma-\frac{23}{6}+\zeta(4)-4\zeta(3)+6\zeta(2)\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

Although intermediate terms in the sum become exponentially large, the values
 themselves become exponentially small:
\begin_inset Formula \[
b_{n}=\mathcal{O}\left(n^{1/4}e^{-2\sqrt{\pi n}}\right)\]

\end_inset 

 The development of an explicit expression for the asymptototic behaviour
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset 

 is the main focus of this essay.
 The principal result is that 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
b_{n}=\left(\frac{2n}{\pi}\right)^{1/4}\exp\left(-\sqrt{4\pi n}\right)\cos\left(\sqrt{4\pi n}-\frac{5\pi}{8}\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(n^{-1/4}e^{-2\sqrt{\pi n}}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The method of attack used to obtain this result is to convert the Newton
 series into an integral of the Norlund-Rice form
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Fla94}

\end_inset 

, which may be evaluated using steepest-descent/stationary-phase methods
 [need ref].
 These techniques are sufficiently general that they can be applied to other
 similar sums that appear in the literature [multiple refs].
 One of the prinicpal results of this essay is to apply this asymptotic
 expansion to the Newton series for the Dirichlet 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset 

-functions.
 Additional results concern the generalization of 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset 

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $b(s)$
\end_inset 

 for generalized complex 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $b(n)=b_{n}$
\end_inset 

 at the integers 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

Another set of sections explore the relationship to the Stieltjes constants,
 and attempt to find an asymptotic expansion for these.
\layout Standard

