Generating Functions
\layout Standard

The ordinary and the exponential generating functions for the coefficients
 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset 

 are readily obtained; these are presented in this section.
\layout Theorem

The ordinary generating function is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\beta(z) & = & \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}b_{n}z^{n}\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{-1}{2(1-z)}+\frac{z}{(1-z)^{2}}\left[\ln(1-z)+\psi\left(\frac{1}{1-z}\right)\right]\label{eq:}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset 

 is the digamma function.
\layout Proof

The above may be obtained by straightforward substitution follwed by an
 exchange of the order of summation.
 The harmonic numbers lead to the logarithm via the identity 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\ln(1-z)=-\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{z^{k}}{k}\]

\end_inset 

 while the binomial series re-sums to the digamma function, which has the
 Taylor's series 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\psi(1+y)=-\gamma+\sum_{n=2}^{\infty}(-1)^{n}\zeta(n)y^{n-1}\]

\end_inset 

 (equation 6.3.14 from Abramowitz and Stegun
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{A&S}

\end_inset 

).
 
\layout Standard

The above simplifies considerably, to
\begin_inset Formula \[
\beta\left(\frac{w-1}{w}\right)=\frac{w}{2}+(w-1)(\psi(w)-\ln w)\]

\end_inset 

upon substitution of 
\begin_inset Formula $z=(w-1)/w$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

An exponential generating function is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}b_{n}\frac{z^{n}}{n!}=e^{z}\left[z\left(1-\gamma+\mbox{Ein}(z)\right)-\frac{1}{2}+\sum_{k=2}^{\infty}\frac{(-z)^{k}}{k!}\zeta(k)\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ein}(z)$
\end_inset 

 is the entire exponential integral: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mbox{Ein}(z)=-\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{k}\frac{(-z)^{k}}{k!}=e^{-z}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}H_{n}\frac{z^{n}}{n!}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}$
\end_inset 

 are the harmonic numbers.
