Relation to the Stieltjes constants
\layout Standard

The standard power series for the Riemann zeta function is written as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta(s)=\frac{1}{s-1}+\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{(-1)^{n}}{n!}\gamma_{n}(s-1)^{n}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{n}$
\end_inset 

 are known as the Stieltjes constants.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset 

 can be related to these by re-expressing the binomial coefficient as a
 power series.
 That is, the binomial coefficient is just a polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
s\\
n\end{array}\right)=\frac{(s)_{n}}{n!}=\frac{(-1)^{n}}{n!}\sum_{k=0}^{n}(-1)^{k}\left[\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right]s^{k}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 with coefficients given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset 

, the Stirling Number of the First Kind.
 The sign convention used here is that the Stirling numbers are given by
 the recursion relation
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
n+1\\
k\end{array}\right]=n\left[\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k-1\end{array}\right]\]

\end_inset 

 making them all positive, and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
n\\
0\end{array}\right]=\delta_{n,0}\]

\end_inset 

 This convention differs by a sign from the other common convention for
 the Stirling numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $s(n,k)$
\end_inset 

, as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right]=(-1)^{n-k}s(n,k)\]

\end_inset 

 Straightforward substitution leads to 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{(-1)^{m}}{m!}\gamma_{m}=\sum_{n=m}^{\infty}\frac{b_{n}}{n!}\,\sum_{k=m}^{n}(-1)^{k}\left[\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right]\left(\begin{array}{c}
k\\
m\end{array}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The operator
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
G_{nm}=(-1)^{m+1}\sum_{k=m}^{n}(-1)^{k}\left[\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right]\left(\begin{array}{c}
k\\
m\end{array}\right)\label{eq:g_nm}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 is lower-triangular.
 There is an even simpler, amusing identity which may be obtained by exchanging
 the order of integration: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{(-1)^{m}}{m!}\gamma_{m}=\sum_{k=m}^{\infty}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
k\\
m\end{array}\right)\sum_{n=k}^{\infty}\frac{b_{n}}{n!}\,\left[\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

The first sum sum be recognized as the so-called binomial transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\{ s_{m}\}$
\end_inset 

 of a series 
\begin_inset Formula $\{ a_{k}\}$
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \[
s_{m}=\sum_{k=m}^{\infty}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
k\\
m\end{array}\right)a_{k}\]

\end_inset 

 Such a transform is an involution, so that its inverse is given by
\begin_inset Formula \[
a_{n}=\sum_{m=n}^{\infty}(-1)^{m}\left(\begin{array}{c}
m\\
n\end{array}\right)s_{m}\]

\end_inset 

 Applying this to the above leads to the amusing identity 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{c_{k}}{k!}=\sum_{m=k}^{\infty}\frac{\gamma_{m}}{m!}\left(\begin{array}{c}
m\\
k\end{array}\right)=\sum_{n=k}^{\infty}\frac{b_{n}}{n!}\left[\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right]\]

\end_inset 

 where the constants 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{k}$
\end_inset 

 correspond to derivatives of the zeta function at 
\begin_inset Formula $s=0$
\end_inset 

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\zeta(s)=\frac{1}{s-1}+\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}c_{k}\,\frac{(-s)^{k}}{k!}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The relationship between the constants 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset 

 and the Stieltjes constants provide a possible avenue for exploring the
 asymptotic behaviour of the Stieltjes constants.
 This is explored in the next section.
\layout Section

