Review of Dirichlet Series
\layout Standard

The following sections consider sums with 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta(s)$
\end_inset 

 in the denominator.
 There are many Dirichlet series that acheive this.
 The canonical one, involving the Mobius function is
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{\mu(n)}{n^{s}}=\frac{1}{\zeta(s)}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 But there is also one for the Euler Phi function:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{\phi(n)}{n^{s}}=\frac{\zeta(s-1)}{\zeta(s)}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The Liouville function:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{\lambda(n)}{n^{s}}=\frac{\zeta(2s)}{\zeta(s)}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The von Mangoldt function 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{\Lambda(n)}{n^{s}}=-\frac{\zeta^{\prime}(s)}{\zeta(s)}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 There are a dozen others that can be readily found in introductory textbooks
 and/or the web.
 
\layout Standard

One may construct in a very straightforward way the Dirichlet series for
 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\zeta(s-a)$
\end_inset 

 for any complex 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset 

, as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\zeta(2s-a)$
\end_inset 

.
 These can be constructed by a faily trival application of Dirichlet convolution
, together with the Mobius inversion formula.
 In short, one has an old, general theorem that
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{(f*g)(n)}{n^{s}}=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{f(n)}{n^{s}}\;\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\frac{g(m)}{m^{s}}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f*g$
\end_inset 

 is the Dirichlet convolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
(f*g)(n)=\sum_{d|n}f(d)g\left(\frac{n}{d}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Since Dirichlet convolution is invertible whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $f(1)\ne1$
\end_inset 

 (and/or 
\begin_inset Formula $g(1)\ne1$
\end_inset 

), one may mulltiply and divide Dirichlet series with impunity, more or
 less.
 
\layout Standard

I havent yet seen a way of building 
